The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a fate."
“Nor are healthy young women isolated, because they help with the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, works in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
It issued an information brochure that should help prevent witch-hunts.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah was killed last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with petrol and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate set of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman caught fire in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught on fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" of the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
“Gambian President Jammeh, following the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging hunt for the witches who allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic.”
“To help him, he brought in shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly selected from the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released around a thousand people in detention.
Bakala’s Tenant: He warms up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly and stubborn man walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving his sentence.
All three have just been caught up in rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, there is no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in the new contract of his son, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a gesture.
“Everybody says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large liberalisation testing laboratory.
After the New Year will occur with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That is why Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine o’clock, was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number machine.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost does not give time even to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the room crowd is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve usual problems, as in the old days: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting," respond, after briefly doubting the workers who are in it when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the former Bakala miners’ flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of the Parliament, Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaorálek of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, treated them loudly and clearly and now they appear continuously in newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want new soil."
“They didn’t even change my fucking bathroom plate,” the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, at the moment more than anything retirees come to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rental in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the employee of the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge will have to settle the matter.
“This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and completely in accordance with the law,” warns RPG on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man in the street in front of the customer service center gives at least part of the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,” he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"Current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, adding that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG could with the rents invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rental in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
“In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square meter per month,” the screen reads.
Only 38% increase the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 kroner per square meter,” says RPG.
At 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) back on the floors, mainly in saving on heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides in its interior a small nursery with everything proper to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
From the very first sketches of the Avriopoint building, the architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known buildings in Brno emerged, thought of including a space for its mini-kindergarten.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow the architects and draughtsmen to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-kindergarten was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's childcare centre is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding (more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the mini-kindergarten in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified personnel. In addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present for their care all day. The nursery currently houses children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they go more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten programme are comparable to the regular preschool programme.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach up to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children from school late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyal relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced staff marketing.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. See Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and wildlife.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us even inside.
The corrugated wood copies the window frames, railings, door trim, peepholes and signs.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia, emerged from the remodeling of a house of the year 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Park G<0xC3><0xBC>ell, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During the construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect at all the construction rules of the time and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
It annoyed him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, quite the opposite: just fifteen days after the city council’s request, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage list.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most overloaded apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry to other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
