How to choose the mattress and the box spring: women and men look for different things
Nothing like a pompous bed frame; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie on, that is, the mattress and the box spring.
First of all, they must complement each other perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
During the election numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, state of health and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and box spring are located is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that usually does not have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them over more frequently.
If the canals in the center are not properly aerated and above are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside. Even mold can appear below.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, hard surface.
“Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
“This type of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have long-term nervous system problems, so they receive poorly information from the joints and the skin,” explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to be able to appreciate viscoelastics.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes your stiffness and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, he won’t lap like after a hard game.
He just sleeps better.
The viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to your height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed of between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example singles, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
“If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards your elbows,” advises the engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert at Cechu <0xC4><0x8D>aloun<0xC3><0xAD>k<0xC5><0xAF> a dekoratér<0xC5><0xAF>, who has already been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for many years.
In double rooms, each one needs its own box spring and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bed bases at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with interior springs a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When you touch it with your hand or sit on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of box spring.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe poorly and you can not wash their cover, which today is often done.
And, since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject the slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
That's why sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully take care of cleaning and washing the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be removed and washed easily.
Although mattress covers with zipper closure are currently manufactured throughout its perimeter, so when you open them they stay in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), its manipulation in the larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a box spring, do you have a firm board?
Never! Never!
As much for the beds designed to spend a night visits.
However, you must make (if you do not already have) ventilation holes in the table and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulable sheet bedsprings containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) may be used, although a bedspring with a larger number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar área are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated is always better.
Articulating sheet bed bases should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to recline.
In addition to the adjustment of the stiffness of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows pressing or even tilting the sheets in such a way that they "surround" perfectly to the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very broad shoulders, this is very important.
They are even remembered by the manufacturers of mattresses who, in the "males", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are bed bases with cross or slat structure with the so-called multi-twist damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and box spring, if you use a bad pillow (large and "fluffy"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can be relaxed.
The recommended size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the pillowcase with shoulder support or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in vogue.
Petroleum-based raw materials, with which polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soy.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers employ soy.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek of the company Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh scent to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" with breeze vegetable extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "warm up" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warmth.
The favorites right now?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with a structure of adapted cells, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold foam and viscoelastic make it possible to manufacture mattresses of various zones that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as sanitary means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and box springs.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam adhered to the cover for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is free.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cellular structure and high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoff astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents are using people-tracking devices to monitor their children
The fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to be informed about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
“We are all trying to tell ourselves that this is not spying, but another way to reduce the chances of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
“I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone’s bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková warns that if the child does not want to take it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.”
“Before, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be switched off as easily as the tracking device,” says Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it’s a pre-arranged kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check to see if the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that can reveal their location.”
"Now it's the phone."
“As the use of tracking devices spreads, so will the search for them, since their sale will certainly be made with a lot of publicity.”
“In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
“The device can be set to regularly send the position after a certain period of time.”
“If he suffers damage, he will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question.”
“The most expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stands still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says <0xC4><0x8C>ech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with mobile smartphones with navigation, on which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can get lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, that’s why they’re currently testing devices that look like a digital clock.
“In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device.”
“Or identify it after a certain amount of time, which can buy the police time,” he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging up, they will still use the same technology that is used for vehicle tracking.
This involves checking the position with a GPS system (which is used in regular navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to encircle the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to set off explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense added to its arsenal 224 kilometers of wick.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the lifespan of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the fuse for explosives from the STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES by justifying the purchase of such an enormous amount of wick by saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of wick a year.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnicians of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided however that, in such a case, they should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want to exempt either Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could it be justified that the army should spend sixty kilometers of wick.
This is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if this were the case, the army would have sufficient stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional comes with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the Rapid Intervention Brigade complained to Minister Vondra in person recently because they say they have very little ammunition for various weapons, so even money-related shooting practices are limited.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"Nor can I understand that we repeatedly buy such quantities of wick."
“But it’s their decision, and they’ll certainly know why they’re acting like that.”
“For us, the army is a good customer that, as a company, we try to satisfy,” admits the commercial director of STV Group, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick, saying he will have stockpiles of this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD> of the STV Group points out that the fuse only has a useful life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, two years.
“If it is stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,” says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, it obtained a discount.
“They cost us 60 percent less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Defense Ministry’s procurement center.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of wicks by police pyrotechnics, which remove ammunition from World War II or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for the right amount to deplete the ammunition before the end of its useful life.
They decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be achieved.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old wick will have to be removed, which is now being bought "cheap".
So far I'm still living from the contacts I got thanks to the contest
Winning the "Entrepreneur of the Year" competition helped Luká<0xC5><0xA1> Pytloun sell his hotel franchises.
The last edition, won the contest "Entrepreneur of the year" the 28-year-old entrepreneur Luká<0xC5><0xA1> Pytloun from Liberec.
Their success story seems to be taken from a movie.
Luká<0xC5><0xA1> Pytloun loved to travel.
Abroad he realized that in Liberec quality accommodation was needed at a good price.
With the savings he gathered from seasonal jobs abroad and a bank loan he bought a house that was half-ruined composed of five floors.
Considering he was still in his third year of college, he was really brave.
“Today, the value for money of accommodation in our area pushed me to do something about it,” says Luká<0xC5><0xA1> Pytloun.
He began to rent the rebuilt first floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned he invested back into the building, which he gradually converted into a 54-room pension.
Since then, in seven years in the business, he gradually managed to open in Liberec four guesthouses, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year opened another one of the same quality.
“We have just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise,” the No. 1 entrepreneur said last year.
“This sale of licenses for the opening of hotels greatly helped the fact of winning the ‘Entrepreneur of the Year’ contest,” Pytloun adds gratefully.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and the surrounding area.
“People recognized me on the street, they still congratulated me often and, I must say, I was very nice,” he recalls.
Without a doubt, it recommends everyone to try some company that participates in the contest.
But he believes that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He states that, so far, he continues to live on contacts and acquaintances that, without the competition, he might not have obtained.
"With some people I met thanks to the contest I started to collaborate regularly."
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in the employees,
In total, about 70.
“I’ve seen them show greater loyalty and are proud to participate in something that gained general recognition.”
“It’s not, by any means, my own personal success, but it’s the result of the hard work of the whole team.”
“It’s only my name that appears on the front page,” Luká<0xC5><0xA1> Pytloun says modestly today.
To my successor I wish a quieter year than we have had in Farmet
The euphoria over the victory was soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the hard work of the winner, it is possible that Farmet has already gone through the worst.
The owner of the Farmet company, Karel <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>, received the first prize in the latest edition of Vodafone's "Company of the Year" competition, last year in the "Slavic House" in Prague.
The jury appreciated his efforts, with which he managed to turn a small technical workshop in <0xC4><0x8C>eská Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
“I can say that the award not only encouraged me, but all my collaborators and improved our confidence to fight against the competition,” says last year’s winner.
The history of the Farmet company begins with the desire to do something useful.
That is why, when the state proposed to Karel <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>’s father the rental of a small workshop as compensation for the seizure of properties during communism, he did not hesitate too much; he resigned his position in the company in which he worked and, with a couple of colleagues, they founded the company with his father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in central Europe.
They obtained a greater presence also among the non-specialized public after achieving success in the contest in the media.
“Not only did our customers start to consider the Farmet brand as considerably better, but also foreign partners started to value the collaboration with a company that was more successful in their country,” says Karel <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>.
Last year was perhaps not in Farmet only a sample of the euphoria of the victory.
It also gained recognition for its commercial results up to 2008 and, partially, 2009.
And 2009 was the hardest year for machinery sales.
The worsening of the crisis, which had not yet reached so many citizens, caused companies to stop their investment projects and begin to limit the purchase of new machines or technologies.
"We, of course, are not free of such a situation either."
“The revenues were reduced by 40%, we had to limit production and we even had some layoffs,” explains Karel <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>.
A viable company must, at times, adopt even unpopular measures.
However, they controlled the situation and maintained the company’s profits, although at lower levels than before the crisis.
In spite of everything, where Farmet did not cut expenses was in research and development.
“With the grants we have built a research and training center, strengthened the presence in the international market and obtained magnificent valuations at national fairs,” says <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>.
Everything indicates that they have already left the crisis behind.
Revenues are rising again and, with them, the number of new employees.
“The new achievement is expected to bring a sense of victory, but in a calmer atmosphere,” says Karel <0xC5><0xBD><0xC4><0x8F>ársk<0xC3><0xBD>.
A survey that reveals the ridiculous rules
The Absurdity of the Year survey is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity of the Year survey was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than a third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration asked for an extract from the commercial register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when it carries out a check on the insured's taxes," <0xC4><0x8C>SSZ spokeswoman Jana Bura<0xC5><0x88>ová said.
The objective of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year for the fourth time he is part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodá<0xC5><0x99>ské noviny and begins to create a following among the general public.
While last year’s edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it practically reached four thousand.
And it is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations to spare that must be respected simply to trade.
"Perhaps in the number of papers required for tax filing we are in first place worldwide," says Karel Havl<0xC3><0xAD><0xC4><0x8D>ek of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
Simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments for years.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, the Czech Republic is in the 74th position, that is, eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first held in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Afterwards, the organizer of the contest chooses seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
Win the absurdity that gets the most votes.
For this year’s survey, more than 100 were submitted, including 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by both businessmen and professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year’s seventy proposals is published on the pages of the contest.
The announcement of the contest, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, the event was attended by Eva Svobodová, Director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, and Petr Ku<0xC5><0xBE>el, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state continually puts obstacles in the way of entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade," announced Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations do not stay in borage water.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the employer's obligation to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a post at a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. communication to the labor office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
The third one is the winner.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
Therefore, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
A new category recognizes socially responsible companies
Ecological, humanitarian, educational or sports projects are valued.
The novelty in this fifth edition of the Hospodá<0xC5><0x99>ské noviny contest is the category called Responsible Company of the year 2010.
The purpose of this competition is to support responsible and fair companies.
“In this way we want to support companies that deal with the impact of their activity on the environment and that support socially responsible activities,” says Patrik Bartholdy, regional director of the mobile operator of the company Vodafone, organizer and sponsor of the contest, as in the case of the Rebel of the Year contest.
For this new special subcategory of this year’s edition of Vodafone Empresa’s main competition of the year 2010, companies were presented for which commercial success is not the only long-term objective.
The story of each of them is inspiring and would allow us to write an independent article.
Although the type of activities varies completely from one to the other, the common denominator is the support and consideration they offer.
In one case, it involves disabled people, in another, personal or health problems of employees.
Among the fourteen finalists from all over the Republic was, for example, the Prague software company Et Netera, which supports the formation of informal sports teams among its workers, who then participate in tournaments of various sports.
Another example of a company responsible for the Pardubice area is the company Isolit-Bravo, which has already been the main donor of funds to sponsor disabled children for seven years.
In Pod<0xC4><0x9B>brad, there is a stationery company that is particularly concerned with the health problems of its workers, since they constitute more than 70% of the workforce; for this reason it received the title of Company responsible for the central area of Czechia and in the Vodafone Company of the year competition it finished third in the region.
In Olomouc won the accounting firm MiRyz Soft, which reduced working hours, even below the average of 35 hours per week, without reducing wages.
The title was also awarded because it primarily buys from Czech manufacturers, supports community activities in the area and respects the environment.
“We try to recycle as much as possible so that our production and management activities produce the least possible impact on the environment,” explains entrepreneur Milu<0xC5><0xA1>e Ryznarová.
The responsible IT company Enlogit from the <0xC3><0x9A>st<0xC3><0xAD> region also thinks about the health of its employees and, with each laptop, offered them an ergonomic chair and keyboards; in addition, it supports work from home and at its business events uses the catering services of a local protected company.
“In addition, we support the Person in Distress grant, which specifically helps the local Roma community,” says Ond<0xC5><0x99>ej Such<0xC3><0xBD>.
The Karlovy Vary region's Pran<0xC3><0xAD> a <0xC4><0x8D>i<0xC5><0xA1>t<0xC4><0x9B>n<0xC3><0xAD> laundry company, whose employees receive special bonuses that have an impact on their pension funds, is also well-placed with a mention.
“We give benefits in food, transport, improving qualifications and leisure,” says Josef Strapa<0xC4><0x8D> of Bruntál Czasch construction company, winner in the Moravian-Silesian region.
In the Responsible Company of the Year category, all regional finalists of the Vodafone Company of the Year competition who answered the questions on the registration form were automatically nominated and sent to the organisers before 15 August.
The organizers removed forms that were not complete or wrong from the evaluation.
"If the representatives of the contesting companies did not answer the questions, they could not participate in the Responsible Company of the Year contest, but they are not disqualified from the "main" Vodafone Company of the Year contest."
“Individual entries for this competition are not permitted, as this is a subcategory of the main Company of the Year competition,” explains Karel Goldman of Bison & Rose.
Police made arrests during a public auction at the Agricultural Fund building in Pilsen
Anti-corruption police made several arrests at the Agricultural Fund building in recent days.
Detectives handcuffed a local media entrepreneur and real estate entrepreneur Lubo<0xC5><0xA1> G.
It seems that this attempt to manipulate an ongoing public auction for the restitution of rights in such a way that the auctioned land would be received by a precise interested party.
He had to pay Lubo<0xC5><0xA1> G. half a million kroner for it.
"At the moment I can only say that the police are looking for a person for bribery during a public auction and public tender," Pilsen chief prosecutor Antonie Zelená told Právo, adding that for the time being she could not divulge further details about the ongoing investigation.
After 24 hours, police released the 46-year-old businessman.
On the way in which it could influence the public auction, given the little official information, one can only speculate.
The spokeswoman for the Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>ra <0xC4><0x8C>erná Agricultural Fund responded to Právo’s questions by saying that the police actually carried out the arrest at the Pilsen headquarters and it was during a public auction.
“This is a customer, not one of our employees,” he said.
According to <0xC4><0x8C>erná, the public auction is called "Call for proposals for land transfer in accordance with the Land Law" and is carried out when several interested parties appear in relation to the offered land.
"These people, during the call, offer a value higher than that of their restitution, which must be transferred before the value of the land is announced."
"Based on the offers, the order of buyers is determined and then the Agricultural Fund transfers the land to the person offering the highest offer," the Fund spokeswoman explained.
Lubo<0xC5><0xA1> G. had information as to who was to be invited to the auction and, since he was also an interested person because he had acquired various rights of restitution, he proposed to those interested in the land that he would not participate in the auction.
For that, he was charging a commission.
This would explain why, at the time of the arrest, he had so much money on him.
Lubo<0xC5><0xA1> G. had special contacts in the Pilsen Fund for a long time.
It was in the case of the former head of the PF, Václav Sankot, who was charged with clearing the replacement of land for which a construction decision had already been issued.
For example, Lubo<0xC5><0xA1> G. has just obtained land from the Fund for the construction of public infrastructure, in particular on the site where a major road should be built to the industrial area of Borská pole.
Later, he exchanged them in a very beneficial way with the magistrate for a house in the historic center of the city with a much higher value.
In this case, the city council had to intervene because, otherwise, the blocked land would prevent construction.
Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred kroner per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to take several hundred kroner more out of their wallets from January than they do now.
The price of electricity rises by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kroner more per year than now.
However, the main electricity suppliers reduced prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaics, has increased.
However, the gas is moderately expensive, especially at the time when heating is used the most and, therefore, the consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also count on a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The increase in prices is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 kroner a month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 kroner a year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not vary, Praguens will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
The rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, can increase considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns about 2,500 apartments in <0xC3><0x9A>st<0xC3><0xAD> nad Labem, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court those who disagree with the new lease.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of about 300,000 flats, could rise as much as 10 percent next year.
Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer in mode, because it slowly takes effect
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
Those are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because they take a long time to get drunk."
"Now the fashion is strong alcoholic beverages," Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelikán, head of pediatrics at Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia, tells Právo.
"When they manage to get a bottle to their father from the pantry, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and doesn’t smell as much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesperson of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Usually it's Fernet or rum."
“Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.”
“In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home,” Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, they are thirteen- and fourteen-year-old drinkers who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
“It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 of alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy,” the department doctor says of this case.
"He was at the Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at some dance party."
“The interesting thing is that his mother wasn’t even surprised that her daughter disappeared for 48 hours,” the boss said.
It is precisely the parents’ lack of interest or even their children’s clear tolerance for drinking that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependence.
"Alcoholic is understood to be a person who has a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in the pediatric clinic of Motol forty drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the walking medical examination, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: the day of witches, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad notes or, on the contrary, they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
“On Witch Day, I’ve seen up to seven drunk children admitted at a time,” Pelikan adds.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
The morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"They take it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and nothing hurts."
“They’re just confused about where they are,” says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their temper at least when they see the expenses they’ve incurred.
Ambulance and hospitalization in a room for critically ill patients can cost tens of thousands of kroner.
“I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a job for young people so that you would earn enough to pay for that night,” Pelikán adds.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are in third-party hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa - EADS aircraft is located.
It is the first time such a device has been found in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad to carry out internship or demonstration flights.
This is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-seaters.
These are still preserved in Aer Vodochody and the intermediary of the sale, the company Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peje<0xC5><0xA1>k, from the defence press department, says it is not yet known when the planes will be physically removed from Vodochody.
"The single-seat L-159 aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, without additional investments or contributions from the Ministry."
"The L-159T1 two-seaters were exchanged in their current state," he told Pravo Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek.
