The Democratic Routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private companies.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it makes it possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively humor that reigns in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in a number of countries along the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a reduced 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a large decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents from Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44 per cent of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same as last year, but considerably higher than the 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (figure 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted their country ' s Congress and 45 per cent their government, the same as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has held up during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32 per cent.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America cite crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent say they or a close relative have been a victim of crime in the past year, down from 38 per cent last year and the lowest percentage since 1995.
The more positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, compared to only 56 per cent in 2007 (see figure 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
Elections in the trash
No one expected the November 28 general election in Haiti to be perfect.
But it was far worse than feared by foreigners trying to help the country recover from its troubles.
Votes were introduced at the polls, some people voted several times, ballots were thrown in the sewers, polling stations were destroyed and acts of intimidation were carried out.
The polling stations opened hours late.
Numerous Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, were wandering the area trying to figure out where they had to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, denounced fraud and called for the annulment of the elections.
The protests, some of them violent, spread across the country.
But Edmond Mulet, the highest-ranking United Nations official in Haiti, said they were "relatively good choices in many ways."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautioned that "we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which its opponents say is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, should announce the preliminary results on Dec. 7.
The tiebreaker is expected to take place in January.
All hopes for the elections have not yet been lost.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial petition calling for the invalidation of the vote.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr. Célestin, who has hardly any support, if any, has moved on to the second round.
Given that the cholera epidemic is sweeping the country and more than a million earthquake survivors are still living in tents, a large abstention is expected.
When the time came, many Haitians wanted to vote, but failed to do so due to a lack of organization.
About 250,000 identity documents needed to vote had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
There's a lot at stake.
Aid donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an essential step in Haiti’s reconstruction.
And, as it has become clear, so do Haitians themselves.
Advancing tiptoe to the center
In the weeks since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernandez, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed great public sympathy that has increased her popularity rate by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level she has recorded since her election in 2007.
Still, whether she can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year’s election will depend on whether the clearly affected Ms. Fernandez puts aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Nestor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are inconclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, was in the habit of crafting budgets that undervalued tax revenues, economic growth, and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend the additional income at its discretion.
In theory, Ms. Fernandez’s government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened after Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the Peronist movement in power have clashed with Ms. Fernández.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one MP punched another in the face and other MPs accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
“I’m not going to argue,” the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore apply to next year, giving the President even more scope to spend it.
The economy is improving considerably: it will probably grow by as much as 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the wage demands of the unions, place it near 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, put pressure on the private sector and had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernandez moderate these policies now?
It has convened meetings between the private sector and trade union leaders.
In addition, its officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18 percent.
The economy has been boosted by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the growth boost achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason, Mrs. Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina’s financial ties with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
Currently, it seems that Mrs. Fernández is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is usually the case.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer “technical assistance” to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems the prelude to the cleaning up of the INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernandez wants to stay in politics after her term ends, given that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If it does, it will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have waned.
If she wants to win another election, she’ll have to decide whether or not to quietly repudiate many of her husband’s policies.
