The lion is ready to roar again, as MGM’s restructuring gets final court approval
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally got the green light to start over.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the “pre-armed” plan by creditors to erase approximately $5 billion of debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and premiering movies and TV shows.
Thursday’s ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal hurdles for MGM to relaunch under Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the chief executives of what will be a scaled-down studio.
Staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320.
In reality, MGM will not exit Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a planned $500 million credit facility to fund the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the loan, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio’s restructuring process began in May 2009, when investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to advise on the management needed to sort out its finances, as it struggled to make interest payments of $300 million a year.
In August, Principal Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron President and bankruptcy recovery expert, known for his work on Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper’s attempts to resolve MGM’s financial woes and satisfy the studio’s more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, in late 2009 the parties agreed to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders and none willing to pay the more than $2 billion sought by creditors.
Before the spring of this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of internal debate and disagreements, was finally backed by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially comes out of bankruptcy in the coming weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies will receive multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will get a $9.5 million payment.
Cooper’s companies, which have been raising $375,000 per month for their company management services, will receive a “success fee” of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which released only one film this year, and put together an annual slate of seven or eight films to come out in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on “The Hobbit,” along with Warner Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM’s debt, had been trying to arrange a studio merger with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent talks between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
