A more moderate side of law enforcement in China is promoted
As an urban drill sergeant, Tang Shenbin paced a city plaza, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan, the burly policemen of China’s urban order, feared and despised for their capricious forceful measures and penchant for violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firm!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely passed adolescence with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed above the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
“Personally, I think they look normal,” Mr. Tang said dismissively.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a bachelor’s degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: in 2009, according to one report, 50 officers surrounded a ramshackle snack cart, and watched it with a frown constantly for half an hour, until the peddler picked up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough cop a softer, feminine side.
Regrettably, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s tiny respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors from Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after he used his mobile phone to film them as they dissolved a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and posted on the internet, describing how to effectively flog criminals without making them bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon peddler suffered brain damage after a brawl with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded “a really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district solicited through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered if the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district notice called for female candidates ages 18 to 22, with a good figure "and five harmonious facial features."
They must have a height above average, greater than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Withdrawal at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too arduous for women over 25.
“His image is the important thing,” an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
“First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc.”
Then comes the temperament “and the inner qualities.”
The female chengguan are like vases, she said, adding, “in addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities.”
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to back up that description.
But he noted that height requirements were standard in many Chinese job ads for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
If this means being handsome, it is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the disabled or disfigured should not show up.
"We can't allow a cougar or a hunchback to come to work here," Mr Zheng said.
“His image wouldn’t be good.”
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old, with his cheeks colored and a subtly curved mouth.
She doesn’t think the accent on her looks is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" he asked with a sardonic look.
His dimpled co-worker, 21-year-old Xu Yang, said “Our work should present the image of the city.”
They also don’t object to their time-bound work, they said, because they harbor greater career ambitions than simply chasing salespeople down the alleys where they’re supposed to circumscribe their business.
Each morning, the squad faces roughly a dozen street vendors who launch themselves on foot or by bicycle, trying to sell as many muffins or tofu bowls as possible before being thrown out.
"Mr. Wang, you have to leave."
"We've told you many times!" said Miss Xu as a salesman escaped on foot, temporarily abandoning his bicycle-drawn cart with noodle garnishes.
Officers describe their duties as more monotonous than exhausting.
“This is pretty much the same every day,” said Huang Jing, 20, who studies marketing in his spare hours.
"Very routine."
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate merchandise from vendors.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public displays of animosity against bureaucracy, which are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the provincial capital of Yunnan, rioted after a false rumor spread that a salesman had been killed by chengguan officers.
More than a dozen police or Chengguan officers were injured in the nighttime episode; 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
For the time being, Xindu has avoided such violence.
But calm is hardly guaranteed.
Just two blocks from the peaceful Baoguang Square, where female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered in a corner.
Officers had confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk instead of in a workshop, as required by regulation.
The owner of the motorcycle was yelling rudely.
The situation stalled for 15 minutes before the officers, with a bad face, elbowed their way to their vehicles and quickly left with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator assigned to the men’s squad, remained behind, his white badge turned to hide his name.
Like female officers, coordinators, men aged 40 and over, play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not taught to maintain an elegant image.
“Sometimes we fight verbally.”
“Sometimes we fight physically,” Mr. Li said quite naturally.
“Most of the time it’s the public that starts the fight.”
Prosecutors will not press charges against Senator Ensign
Attorneys for the senator announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have cleared Senator John Ensign of criminal charges arising from his affair with a former campaign aide and his efforts to secure work through lobbying for the woman’s husband.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered as a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it was "surely pleased" with the decision, which came after a year-long investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of its investigation and that it has no plan to bring charges against him on this issue.”
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have colluded to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, email and other documents first leaked in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, get lucrative work through lobbying, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, over the senator’s affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton a job and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to the documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign aide, he was barred under the law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called “revolving door lobbying ban,” which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
Of the evidence that has been made public, “it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, amid charges of procedural misconduct.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws don’t apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he gave prosecutors.
“I’m not comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we thought they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was merely a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got the job through lobbying thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him he was "crushing" the Home Office over a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a luncheon with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after it had hired Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair first surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters it planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokesman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the Justice Department’s lead and conclude its investigation.
“Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada,” he said.
Cheshire's appeal will target Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chatting" in the rows of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the gruesome testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter posts about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a family from Cheshire, Connecticut, is set to come to an official end, with the death penalty judge’s imposition voted on by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed briefs in court outlining the appeals arguments that are likely to occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reporting on the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “a circus atmosphere,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details made public passions exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appellate judges to grapple with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“Based on what I experienced during this process, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of the new technology in the courtroom is affecting the rights of the individual to have a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, lead counsel for Mr. Hayes’s defense.
