Pakistan's nuclear program raises concerns in the US
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at "a faster rate than any other country."
Wikileaks leaks confirm links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The contents of the correspondence between the U.S. Embassy in Pakistan and the U.S. State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns caused in Washington by the Pakistani nuclear program.
Apart from the enlightening and juicy details they offer about the content of the talks and the thoughts of the US diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that the cooperation between the two countries in atomic security, instead of increasing, "decreases", and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster pace than any other country in the world".
The peculiarity of Pakistan’s nuclear program – that the weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to hinder their destruction in case of attack – is one of the main reasons for vigilance in Washington.
This is what the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists in a report prior to the visit of the then National Security Advisor, James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials."
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is regarded, not only by the US, but also by Russia, as proliferating and reason to keep guard.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in nuclear or missile programs," Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The latest in the documentation leaked by Julian Assange’s website is the dwindling cooperation between the US and Pakistan on issues of nuclear proliferation and Pakistan’s high pace of nuclear weapons production.
An embassy dispatch in May, which described communication with Pakistan as “frustrating,” said: “Transparency is often non-existent; offers of aid go unanswered or are discarded.”
In another message, Peter Lavoy, National Intelligence Officer for South Asia, notes that "despite economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also asked Washington, during a visit by the head of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it “very clear” to the responsible that “the Pakistan Army must end tacit support for terrorist groups.”
