As such, all 188 Interpol countries have indications of identifying or locating Assange “with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition.”
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, as the organization has explained, do consider the so-called network notice freeway to proceed with an arrest -which must be undertaken by the national police force-, especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
