China maintains targets to reduce greenhouse gases
The representative of that country at COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent its greenhouse gas emissions.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, in the last four years his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this matter.
China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and support for pilot programs.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the approval, last year, of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
In China, federal authorities have been working in coordination with state and local authorities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, several multi-year plans, both financed by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, are underway or have already been concluded.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficiency Program, which was implemented during the last five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private sector.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent bulbs by savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, scientific adviser to the government of that country on climate change, said that China's efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tons per person, while in the United States they are 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do the same by 2020, he said.
