Obama Promotes Law on Twitter in Favor of Undocumented Students
“If you agree that passing the Dream Act is appropriate, call your senators and urge them to pass this legislation,” the president tweeted.
President Barack Obama today joined the national mobilization in support of the Dream Act, to legalize undocumented students, with a message on his personal Twitter account.
“If you agree that passing the Dream Act is appropriate, call your senators and urge them to pass this legislation,” Obama tweeted.
His brief message keeps open a cyber link to a broader document that asks the public to immediately communicate with senators, given that the vote on the legislation is imminent.
“With a vote expected to happen soon, now is the time to make your voice heard,” he said.
The message was released after all 42 Republican senators threatened to block the vote on any legislation unless the extension of Bush-era tax cuts and government funding is approved.
Such a blockade, announced in a letter signed by the 42 Republican senators, could affect the vote on the Dream Act and other projects such as the ratification of the new START treaty with Russia against the proliferation of nuclear weapons.
Questioned by the Republican blockade of the Dream Act and other projects, presidential spokesman Robert Gibbs trusted that once the fiscal issue is resolved, a timetable can be set for the rest of the projects.
"I think there's a lot of time..."
"We all agree that we have to resolve the tax issue before the end of the year..."
“I think we can get an agreement at some point on that and then we can plan the sequence of the rest,” he said.
Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid announced Tuesday that he would call for a “debate-closing vote” on the Dream Act, so the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be voted on starting next Thursday in the Senate, although it is more likely next week.
The Senate version of the Dream Act would legalize about 800,000 young people who entered the United States before the age of 16, have stayed in the country for the past five years, and entered an institution of higher education or the military.
But supporters require 60 votes to pass the bill, requiring the help of a handful of Republicans, at a time when pro-project organizations are lobbying intensely to ensure the passage of the bill.
Democrats, most of whom support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
Yet at least one of them, Sen. Ben Nelson of Nebraska, has said he will vote against it, and only one Republican has voiced support for the law, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
Therefore, supporters of the Dream Act require adding several Republicans in case other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most wooed Republicans are Maine Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as outgoing Senator George Lemieux of Florida, who completed Senator Mel Martinez’s term.
Other Republicans who have supported the Dream Act in the past include Orrin Hatch of Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson of Texas, but have said they will not support it again.
Another Republican he supported, John McCain, has not defined his position at this time.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the Dream Act faces the biggest hurdles in the Senate.
