Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The “extraordinary” US revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual mores only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s ominously ridiculing profile has long given cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of public knowledge news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who are dedicated to the occult not only trust what they already know, what reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what I know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as what Newsweek published the week before.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultured person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since heads of state can call each other on the phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have been transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly, we just pretend that we do not know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secretive secrets of the most powerful country in the world considerably affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verdugos".
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, very much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the Internet, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also clear that, with today’s technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novelistic, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has once again created a wired telegraph (telephone).
Video (analog) tapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, while now (digital) CDs only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With the high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys that it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques lead us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being secretly plotted in embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s blunders in its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the fast-unlocked funding promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French faux pas have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged 7.2 billion euros in three years and France committed 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million euros per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best cards to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a large complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation turned out to be appreciable and was appreciated for what it really was worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added in three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks with regard to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that every euro borrowed is equivalent to one euro donated.
Evidently, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to emission reduction that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated ... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (that is, the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France finds no such reasoning useful: it “respects” its 420 million euro commitment by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euro) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euro); see the EU document to see for yourself.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other hand, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has taken care of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term detail in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First of all, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could push forward the discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have hope for the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additional character” and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results “do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated”, acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which follow official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as sweets, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to possibly carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrisome," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, included in the food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even bread bar or chewing gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most “nutritious” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk these “pollutant cocktails” pose to the consumer “is probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
